TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is More Fairness Always Preferred? Self-Esteem Moderates Reactions to Procedural Justice
AU  - Wiesenfeld, Batia M.
AU  - Swann, William B.
AU  - Brockner, Joel
AU  - Bartel, Caroline A.
Y1  - 2007/10/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.20159922
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.20159922
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1235
EP  - 1253
VL  - 50
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Organizational justice researchers have demonstrated that employees are more committed to organizations they believe treat them fairly. Drawing on self-verification theory, five studies showed that the positive relationship between procedural justice and commitment was eliminated among those with low self-esteem. Moreover, results of one study showed that this effect occurred only when self-verification strivings were likely to be salient (i.e., when employees expected their relationships with their organization to be relatively enduring). Finally, an experiment provided evidence that participants' experience of self-verification (feeling known and understood) mediated the interactive effect of procedural justice and self-esteem on their organizational commitment.
AB  - Organizational justice researchers have demonstrated that employees are more committed to organizations they believe treat them fairly. Drawing on self-verification theory, five studies showed that the positive relationship between procedural justice and commitment was eliminated among those with low self-esteem. Moreover, results of one study showed that this effect occurred only when self-verification strivings were likely to be salient (i.e., when employees expected their relationships with their organization to be relatively enduring). Finally, an experiment provided evidence that participants' experience of self-verification (feeling known and understood) mediated the interactive effect of procedural justice and self-esteem on their organizational commitment.
