TY  - JOUR
T1  - Abusive Supervision, Upward Maintenance Communication, and Subordinates' Psychological Distress
AU  - Tepper, Bennett J.
AU  - Moss, Sherry E.
AU  - Lockhart, Daniel E.
AU  - Carr, Jon C.
Y1  - 2007/10/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.20159918
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.20159918
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1169
EP  - 1180
VL  - 50
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study reanalyzes data from Tepper's (2000) two-wave study regarding the effects of subordinates' perceptions of supervisory abuse to assess previously unexamined relationships. As predicted, we found that subordinates who more rather than less strongly perceived that they had been abused by supervisors tended to use regulative maintenance tactics with higher frequency. Further, the positive relationship between abusive supervision and subordinates' psychological distress was exacerbated by subordinates' use of regulative maintenance communications, and that relationship was reduced by subordinates' use of direct maintenance communication. Theoretical and practical implications are discussed.
AB  - This study reanalyzes data from Tepper's (2000) two-wave study regarding the effects of subordinates' perceptions of supervisory abuse to assess previously unexamined relationships. As predicted, we found that subordinates who more rather than less strongly perceived that they had been abused by supervisors tended to use regulative maintenance tactics with higher frequency. Further, the positive relationship between abusive supervision and subordinates' psychological distress was exacerbated by subordinates' use of regulative maintenance communications, and that relationship was reduced by subordinates' use of direct maintenance communication. Theoretical and practical implications are discussed.
